"1564":"1564","1563":"1563","1530":"1530","1562":"1562","15 June 1563":"15 June 1563","1607":"1607","1549":"1549","17 May 1599":"17 May 1599","1636":"1636","1647":"1647","1559":"1559","All Saints Churchyard, Middleton Cheney, Northamptonshire, England":"All Saints Churchyard, Middleton Cheney, Northamptonshire, England","Naseby, Northamptonshire, England":"Naseby, Northamptonshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Agnes","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Latinized version of the Greek name <i>Hagnē</i>, from the feminine form of the adjective <i>hagnos</i> ‘pure, holy’. This was the name of a young Roman virgin martyred in the persecutions instigated by the Roman emperor Diocletian in   ad  303 . She became a very popular saint in the Middle Ages. Her name was early associated with Latin <i>agnus</i> ‘lamb’, leading to the consistent dropping of the initial <i>H-</i> and to her representation in art accompanied by a lamb. The colloquial form <i>Annes</i> led to some confusion with <i>Ann(e)</i> in earlier centuries. Frequent in the medieval period, the name was revived in the 19th century, and has been especially popular in Scotland.  See also  Annis ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705201,"age":15,"year":"1549","julianDay":2286821,"title":"Book of Common Prayer","description":"Book of Common Prayer, a product of the English Reformation, was published in 1549 for assistance in the administration of the sacraments and other rites and ceremonies of the church according to the use of the Church of England. The book outlined morning, evening, and communion prayers and orders for baptism and marriage, thus making England a truly Protestant state.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Book_of_Common_Prayer","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Book of Common Prayer","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705202,"age":24,"year":"1558","julianDay":2290108,"title":"Act of Uniformity","description":"The Act of Uniformity was passed by the Parliament of England and required all people to go to church once a week. The consequence of not attending church was a fine of 12 pence, which was a considerable amount for a poor person.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705205,"age":35,"year":"1569","julianDay":2294126,"title":"State Lottery","description":"A State Lottery was recorded in 1569. The tickets were sold at St. Paul's Cathedral in London.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705206,"age":37,"year":"1571","julianDay":2294856,"title":"The Royal Exchange is Organized","description":"The Royal Exchange was organized in January 1571 by Sir Thomas Gresham. Gresham is known as the father of English banking.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705208,"age":53,"year":"1587","julianDay":2300700,"title":"Elizabeth I Signs Death Warrant for Mary, Queen of Scots","description":"Elizabeth I signed the death warrant for Mary, Queen of Scots, on February 1, 1587, as she was found guilty of plotting to assasinate Elizabeth. Mary, Queen of Scots, was beheaded at Fotheringhay Castle in England on February 8, 1587.","url":"https://www.elizabethi.org/mary_queen_of_scots/","urlTitle":"Elizabeth I.org - Mary Queen of Scots","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Agnes Ulinskas was born in 1534, in Naseby, Northamptonshire, England. She married John Yorke in 1562, in Naseby, Northamptonshire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 3 sons and 2 daughters. She died on 17 May 1599, in her hometown, at the age of 65, and was buried in All Saints Churchyard, Middleton Cheney, Northamptonshire, England."},"et":{"1534–17 May 1599":"1534–17. mai 1599","1530–1607":"1530–1607","1559–Female":"1559–Surnud","1563–1647":"1563–1647","1564–Female":"1564–Surnud","1569–1636":"1569–1636","1572–Male":"1572–Surnud","1534–1599":"1534–1599","22 June 1572":"22. juuni 1572","2 Sep 1569":"2. september 1569","1572":"1572","1571":"1571","27 November 1564":"27. november 1564","before 1559":"enne 1559","15